Kenya is likely to experience poor rains in the March-May long rain season, a regional development authority y has said.Executive secretary Mahboub Maalim of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development delivered the bad news.He said the regional consensus climate outlook for March to May indicates a greater likelihood of below normal to near normal rainfall over much of Kenya, north and east Tanzania, southern Somalia and other parts of the region. But some regions might get flash floods.Maalim briefed the media on drought in the Greater Horn of Africa.He said 20 million people in the region are food insecure and the drought caused 70-100 per cent crop failure in parts of Kenya and Somalia.